  "problem_type": "Causal inference / external validity — distinguishing a real generalizable effect from a real-but-context-specific effect. The test is not broken; the question is whether the result will replicate outside the conditions that produced it.",

  "strategy": "Threat-model the result rather than accept it at face value. Statistical significance answers 'did this happen?' not 'will it happen again under different conditions?' The cognitive task is identifying which threats to validity are most plausible given the specific context clues in the problem.",

  "hardest_part": "Resisting the pull of the surface-level reading: 'significant result → ship it.' The data is real. The lift probably happened. The trap is conflating 'this was true during a 3-day holiday sale' with 'this is true in general.' Those are different claims, and the test only supports the first one. A second trap: p=0.03 with 50k/variant looks robust, so it's easy to feel protected by the numbers when the real threat isn't statistical power at all.",

  "solution": "The likely real explanation is a temporal confound, not a true color effect. Holiday sale traffic is a systematically different population: higher purchase intent, gift-buying behavior, deal-hunting mindset, and a page environment saturated with promotional green (discount badges, sale banners, 'SAVE' callouts). Green may have outperformed blue specifically because it was visually coherent with the surrounding holiday sale aesthetic — not because green buttons generically outperform blue ones. This is an interaction effect: color × context. The 15% lift is probably real within that window; the error is assuming it generalizes. Secondary concerns in order: (1) novelty effect — users clicked the unfamiliar button more, an effect that decays over 1–2 weeks; (2) CTR is a proxy metric — clicking 'Buy Now' is not the same as completing a purchase; (3) a 3-day test cannot capture weekly seasonality cycles. What the team should do before shipping: Re-run the test during a normal traffic period for a minimum of 2 full weeks (to cover at least one weekly cycle and let novelty decay). Measure downstream conversion and revenue per visitor, not just CTR. Segment results by new vs returning users — if the effect is real and generalizable, it should appear across both. If they cannot wait, treat this as a hypothesis that warrants a follow-up test, not a conclusion — ship to 10–20% of traffic with monitoring rather than a full rollout. The p-value is not the problem. The problem is that p-values measure sampling error within a distribution, and holiday shoppers are a different distribution."
